<TITLE> Taiwan plans meeting with Chinese president at APEC </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TAIPEI, Tue Nov 18,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Taiwan's government is arranging a meeting with Chinese President Hu Jintao at a regional summit later this month, an official said on Tuesday, another step in the island's road to improving ties with rival Beijing. Lien Chan, honorary chairman of Taiwan's ruling Nationalist Party and a popular figure among Beijing officials, plans to meet Hu at the Nov. 20-23 Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) leaders summit in Peru. The meeting would be one in a recent series of high-level encounters between the two sides. "I'm looking forward very much to meeting with Chinese leaders and officials to exchange views, in hopes of having thorough talks on cross-Strait trade and financial cooperation," Lien told a news conference. China has claimed self-ruled Taiwan since 1949, when Mao Zedong's forces won the Chinese civil war and Chiang Kai-shek's KMT fled to the island. Beijing has vowed to bring Taiwan under its rule, by force if necessary. But since taking office in May, China-friendly Taiwan President Ma Ying-jeou has quickly improved trade and transit links with China. Increasingly frequent China-Taiwan talks have helped thaw once icy relations, analysts say. "That's the general direction, expanded contact and in the process building enhanced trust," said Raymond Wu, a Taipei-based political risk consultant
